The '''Tesla Model 3''' is a  [[Compact executive car|compact executive]] [[Sedan (car)|sedan]] that is [[Battery electric vehicle|battery powered]] and produced by [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://evfleetworld.co.uk/tesla-model-3-production-still-far-behind-global-demand/ |title=Tesla Model 3 production still far behind global demand |first=Alex |last=Grant |work=EV Fleet World |location=UK |date=November 7, 2017 |access-date=June 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143137/http://evfleetworld.co.uk/tesla-model-3-production-still-far-behind-global-demand/ |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Limited production of the Model 3 began in mid-2017, with the first production vehicle rolling off the assembly line on July 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=881751358407299072|user=elonmusk|title=Model 3 passed all regulatory requirements for production two weeks ahead of schedule. Expecting to complete SN1 on Friday|date=July 2, 2017|access-date=July 4, 2017|first=Elon |last=Musk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hawkins|first=Andrew|date=July 7, 2017|title=Everything you need to know about Tesla Model 3, which is starting production today|website=[[The Verge]]|location=US|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15934756/tesla-model-3-production-electric-car-musk|url-status=live|access-date=July 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709002248/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15934756/tesla-model-3-production-electric-car-musk|archive-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=July 8, 2017|title=Tesla Model 3 – Elon Musk confirms first production unit built|website=Electrek|url=https://electrek.co/2017/07/08/tesla-model-3-production-elon-musk/|url-status=live|access-date=July 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709051304/https://electrek.co/2017/07/08/tesla-model-3-production-elon-musk/|archive-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref> The official launch and delivery of the first 30 cars took place on July 28.<ref>{{cite news|last=Akerstedt|first=Ida|date=July 4, 2017|title=Tesla Model 3 release date 2017 – When is Tesla Model 3 coming out in the UK?|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|url=http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/cars/824678/Tesla-Model-3-release-date-when-coming-out-UK-price-Elon-Musk-electric-car|url-status=live|access-date=July 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704220228/http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/cars/824678/Tesla-Model-3-release-date-when-coming-out-UK-price-Elon-Musk-electric-car|archive-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>

The base Model 3 delivers an [[EPA]]-rated [[all-electric range]] of {{convert|272|mi|abbr=out|0}} and the Long Range version delivers {{convert|358|mi|0 || abbr=out}}.<ref name="tm3web">{{cite web |url=https://www.tesla.com/model3 |title=Model 3 |publisher=Tesla |location=US |year=2019 |access-date=November 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112081646/https://www.tesla.com/model3 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Tesla, the Model 3 carries full [[self-driving]] hardware, with periodic software updates adding functionality.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Siddiqui |first1=Faiz |title=Tesla floats fully self-driving cars as soon as this year |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/17/tesla-floats-fully-self-driving-cars-soon-this-year-many-are-worried-about-what-that-will-unleash/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=December 29, 2019 |date=July 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208044411/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/17/tesla-floats-fully-self-driving-cars-soon-this-year-many-are-worried-about-what-that-will-unleash/ |archive-date=December 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/09/tesla-autopilot-2-5-hardware-computer-autonomous-driving/|title=Tesla has a new Autopilot '2.5' hardware suite with more computing power for autonomous driving|date=August 9, 2017|work=Electrek|access-date=December 8, 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223024911/https://electrek.co/2017/08/09/tesla-autopilot-2-5-hardware-computer-autonomous-driving/|archive-date=December 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tesla.com/autopilot |title=Autopilot |website=tesla.com |access-date=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205070405/https://www.tesla.com/autopilot |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The Model 3 was marketed as being more affordable to more people than previous [[Tesla, Inc.#Automotive products|models by Tesla]]. Since early 2020, the Model 3 is the bestselling electric car in world history,<ref name=Model3TopEV>{{cite news |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/03/10/tesla-passes-1-million-ev-milestone-and-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-seller/ |title=Tesla Passes 1 Million EV Milestone & Model 3 Becomes All Time Best Seller |first=Maximilian |last=Holland |website=CleanTechnica |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412045911/https://cleantechnica.com/2020/03/10/tesla-passes-1-million-ev-milestone-and-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-seller/ |archive-date=April 12, 2020 |url-status=live |quote=Tesla's quarterly reports, meanwhile, had put the Model 3's cumulative sales at 447,980 at the end of 2019. }}</ref> and, in June 2021, became the first electric car to pass the 1&nbsp;million global sales milestone.<ref name=1miModel3>{{cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2021/08/26/tesla-model-3-has-passed-1-million-sales/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Has Passed 1 Million Sales |first=Zachary |last=Shahan |publisher=CleanTechnica |date=August 26, 2021 |access-date=August 26, 2021}}</ref> The Model 3 has been the world's top selling [[plug-in electric car]] (PEV) for three years running, from 2018 to 2020.<ref name="Top20Global2020" /><ref name="Top20Global2018" /><ref name="Top20Global2019" /> It has also been the bestselling PEV in the United States for three consecutive years, 2018 to 2020,<ref name="TopEVs2020US" /><ref name="US2018sales" /><ref name="TopUS2019" /> the top selling PEV in Europe in 2019,<ref name="Model3TopEurope" /> and the bestselling PEV in China in 2020.<ref name="TopNEVsChina2020" />

== History ==
[[File:2019 Tesla Model 3 Performance AWD Rear.jpg|left|thumb|Rear view]]

In an interview for ''[[Wired Science]]'' recorded during 2006<!-- recording; broadcast on PBS 2007-01-04 -->, [[Elon Musk]] presented the {{nowrap|Model 3}} as likely being affordable by most people able to purchase new cars.<ref name="wired-science-interview-2007">{{cite interview|title=Interview with Elon Musk|first=Elon|last=Musk|author-link=Elon Musk|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Onajosm9PWo&t=2m48s|work=[[Wired Science]]|date=January 7, 2007<!-- March 31, 2007 -->|quote=Model 3 is intended to be around a $30,000 price point, so that's really affordable by almost everyone who can buy new cars|access-date=June 15, 2019|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074810/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Onajosm9PWo&t=2m48s|url-status=live}}</ref>  In 2008 the car was stated to be a family car.<ref name="lamonica-20080924">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/teslas-bluestar-to-be-all-electric-family-car/|title=Tesla's 'Bluestar' to be all-electric family car|publisher=[[CNET]]|first=Martin|last=LaMonica|date=September 24, 2008|access-date=September 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215359/https://www.cnet.com/news/teslas-bluestar-to-be-all-electric-family-car/|archive-date=September 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017 Tesla added that the Standard Range version of the all-electric car would have an estimated EPA-rated range of {{convert|215|mi || 0|abbr=out}}, a five-passenger [[seating capacity]], front and rear trunks, and promised sports-car levels of acceleration performance.{{Better source needed|date=April 2018}}<ref name=Model3vsModelS>{{cite press release |url=https://forums.teslarati.com/threads/tesla-publishes-model-3-vs-model-s-specifications-in-employee-only-handout.3609/ |title=Tesla publishes Model 3 vs. Model S specifications in employee-only handout |publisher=Tesla |via=Teslarati Forum |year=2017 |access-date=May 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730014214/https://forums.teslarati.com/threads/tesla-publishes-model-3-vs-model-s-specifications-in-employee-only-handout.3609/ |archive-date=July 30, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-performance-version-spied-test-track/|title=Is this a Tesla Model 3 Performance version spied testing at the Fremont factory?|website=teslarati.com|date=October 18, 2017 |language=en-US|access-date=December 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207140753/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-performance-version-spied-test-track/|archive-date=December 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla said it would have a 5-Star safety rating and have a {{Cd|link=car|long=yes|0.23}}.<ref name=PressKit>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.tesla.com/presskit |title=Press Kit |publisher=Tesla |location=US |access-date=March 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315094117/https://www.tesla.com/presskit |archive-date=March 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> This is lower than the [[Tesla Model S]] {{Cd|long=yes|0.24}}, which, in 2014, was the lowest among the production cars of the time.<ref name="PressKit" />

Within a week of unveiling the Model 3 in 2016, Tesla revealed they had taken 325,000 reservations for the car. These reservations represented potential sales of over {{USD|14 billion}}.<ref name="SFG02042016" /><ref name="325KModel3">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-07/tesla-says-model-3-pre-orders-surge-to-325-000-in-first-week|title=Tesla Says It Received More Than 325,000 Model 3 Reservations|last=Hull|first=Dana|date=April 7, 2016|access-date=April 7, 2016|website=[[Bloomberg News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407192859/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-07/tesla-says-model-3-pre-orders-surge-to-325-000-in-first-week|archive-date=April 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> By August 2017, there were 455,000 net reservations.<ref name="2017reservations">{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/35011-tesla-model-3-reservations-number |title=Elon Musk Finally Reveals the Number of Tesla Model 3 Reservations |first=Jack |last=Crosbie |website=inverse.com |location=US |date=August 2, 2017 |access-date=August 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813082215/https://www.inverse.com/article/35011-tesla-model-3-reservations-number |archive-date=August 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="cnn_money_reservations">{{cite news |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/02/technology/business/tesla-earnings/index.html?iid=hp-stack-dom |title=Tesla now averaging more than 1,800 Model 3 reservations a day |last1=Fiegerman |first1=Seth |date=August 3, 2017 |access-date=August 3, 2017 |work=CNN Money |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803212821/http://money.cnn.com/2017/08/02/technology/business/tesla-earnings/index.html?iid=hp-stack-dom |archive-date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Industry experts were dubious when, in May 2016, Tesla announced its decision to advance its 500,000-total-unit build plan (combined for Model S, [[Tesla Model X|Model X]], and Model 3) to 2018, two years earlier than previously planned, in order to accelerate its target for Model 3 output.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-suppliers/exclusive-suppliers-question-teslas-goals-for-model-3-output-idUSKCN0YB0CA |title=Exclusive: Suppliers question Tesla's goals for Model 3 output |first1=Paul |last1=Lienert |first2=Alexandria |last2=Sage |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=May 20, 2016 |access-date=April 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074238/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-suppliers/exclusive-suppliers-question-teslas-goals-for-model-3-output-idUSKCN0YB0CA |archive-date=April 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-idUSKCN0XV2JL | title=Tesla puts pedal to the metal, 500,000 cars planned in 2018 | first1=Kshitiz | last1=Goliya | first2=Alexandria | last2=Sage | date=May 4, 2016 | agency=[[Reuters]] | access-date=May 7, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507105038/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-idUSKCN0XV2JL | archive-date=May 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Tesla1Q2016>{{cite web | url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2007076272x0x889927/27EE2FDA-9C77-4D6A-8CEE-E8DFE45227BA/Q1_2016_Tesla_Shareholder_Letter.pdf | title=Tesla shareholders letter:Tesla First Quarter 2016 Update | publisher=[[Tesla Inc.]] | date=May 4, 2016 | access-date=May 7, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601053039/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/2007076272x0x889927/27EE2FDA-9C77-4D6A-8CEE-E8DFE45227BA/Q1_2016_Tesla_Shareholder_Letter.pdf | archive-date=June 1, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> As predicted, there were "production bottlenecks" and "production hell". In May 2016, Tesla issued {{USD|2 billion}} in new shares to the stock market to finance the plan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160518/OEM/160519857/tesla-plans-2-billion-stock-sale-to-accelerate-model-3-program |title=Tesla plans $2&nbsp;billion stock sale to accelerate Model 3 program |first=Paul |last=Lienert |newspaper=[[Automotive News]] |location=US |date=May 18, 2016 |access-date=May 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730134700/https://www.autonews.com/article/20160518/OEM/160519857/tesla-plans-2-billion-stock-sale-to-accelerate-model-3-program |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The company plans for the Model 3 are part of Tesla's three-step strategy to start with a high-price vehicle and move progressively towards lower-cost vehicles, while the battery and electric drivetrain were improved and paid for through the sales of the [[Tesla Roadster (2008)|Roadster]], Model S, and Model X vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/new-cars/future-cars/news/a30051/tesla-secret-master-plan-elon-musk-trucks/ |title=Tesla Motors Will Produce a Semi Truck and a Model 3-Based Pickup |first=Chris |last=Perkins |magazine=[[Road & Track]] |date=July 20, 2016 |access-date=August 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802044026/http://www.roadandtrack.com/new-cars/future-cars/news/a30051/tesla-secret-master-plan-elon-musk-trucks/ |archive-date=August 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On April 18, 2018, Tesla updated its production target to 6,000 vehicles per week by the end of June 2018, an increase from its previous target of 5,000 vehicles per week which was previously promised at earlier dates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/news/companies/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-production/index.html|title=Tesla will start working 24/7 to crank out Model 3s|last=Isidore|first=Chris|work=CNNMoney|access-date=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418204050/http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/news/companies/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-production/index.html|archive-date=April 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="fortune.com">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/11/01/tesla-elon-musk-model-3-earnings/|title=Elon Musk Says This Is Tesla's 'Biggest Problem'|website=Fortune|date=November 1, 2017|access-date=November 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105045436/http://fortune.com/2017/11/01/tesla-elon-musk-model-3-earnings/|archive-date=November 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyherald.com/business/20171104/how-the-model-3-delay-is-burning-teslas-other-projects |title=How the Model 3 delay is burning Tesla's other projects |first=Tom |last=Randall |work=Daily Herald |location=Chicago |date=November 4, 2017 |access-date=November 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105060304/http://www.dailyherald.com/business/20171104/how-the-model-3-delay-is-burning-teslas-other-projects |archive-date=November 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="bloomberg.com1">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-01-03/tesla-delays-model-production-goal-as-deliveries-miss-estimates|title=Tesla's Model 3 Challenges Leave Little 'Wiggle Room' on Cash|newspaper=Bloomberg.com|date=January 3, 2018|access-date=January 5, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105004449/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-01-03/tesla-delays-model-production-goal-as-deliveries-miss-estimates|archive-date=January 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 1, 2018, Elon Musk announced that Tesla had met its production goal of 5,000 cars in a week.<ref>{{Cite tweet |first=Elon |last=Musk |number=1013519243030253570 |user=elonmusk |title=7000 cars, 7 days [...] |access-date=July 1, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701204629/https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1013519243030253570 |archive-date=July 1, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://electrek.co/2018/07/01/tesla-model-3-production-milestone-record-total-production-elon-musk/|title=Tesla reaches Model 3 production milestone and record 7,000-car week total production, says Elon Musk|date=July 1, 2018|work=Electrek|access-date=July 1, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701220140/https://electrek.co/2018/07/01/tesla-model-3-production-milestone-record-total-production-elon-musk/|archive-date=July 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-model3-exclusive/exclusive-tesla-hits-model-3-manufacturing-milestone-hours-after-deadline-factory-sources-idUSKBN1JR1WX |title=Exclusive: Tesla hits Model 3 manufacturing milestone, hours after... |first1=Alexandria |last1=Sage |first2=Salvador |last2=Rodriguez |agency=Reuters |location=US |date=July 2, 2018 |access-date=July 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701193312/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-model3-exclusive/exclusive-tesla-hits-model-3-manufacturing-milestone-hours-after-deadline-factory-sources-idUSKBN1JR1WX |archive-date=July 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On February 28, 2019, Tesla announced the availability of the lower-cost, highly anticipated, $35,000, Standard Range trim.<ref name="tesla.com">{{cite news |url=https://www.tesla.com/fr_BE/blog/35000-tesla-model-3-available-now |title=$35,000 Tesla Model 3 Available Now |date=February 28, 2019 |access-date=March 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301102316/https://www.tesla.com/fr_BE/blog/35000-tesla-model-3-available-now |archive-date=March 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, on April 12, 2019, Tesla announced that the Standard Range model would no longer be available for ordering online, but only over the phone or in stores.  [[Tesla Autopilot|Autopilot]], previously a $3,000 option, was included in all versions of the Model 3 except for the Standard Range, while each version's price only increased by $2,000.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a27120534/tesla-model-3-lineup-changes-standard-range/ |title=The "$35,000" Tesla Model 3 Is No More, and It Seems That It Never Was |work=[[Car and Driver]] |location=US |last=Capparella |first=Joey |date=April 12, 2019 |access-date=April 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412183541/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a27120534/tesla-model-3-lineup-changes-standard-range/ |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2019, the Model 3 passed the [[Chevrolet Volt]] to become the all-time bestselling plug-in electric car in the U.S.<ref name=Top3US022019>{{cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/us-electric-car-sales-charted-february-2019/ | title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: February 2019 | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=March 12, 2019 | access-date=March 12, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402145015/https://insideevs.com/us-electric-car-sales-charted-february-2019/ | archive-date=April 2, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Top3US2019>{{cite web |url=https://thedriven.io/2019/04/15/tesla-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-selling-electric-car-in-us/ |title=Tesla Model 3 becomes all-time best-selling electric car in US | first = Bridie | last = Schmidt |work=EV Adoption |publisher=The Driven |date=April 15, 2019 |access-date=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415120510/https://thedriven.io/2019/04/15/tesla-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-selling-electric-car-in-us/ |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Model 3 sales surpassed the [[Nissan Leaf]] in early 2020 to become the world's all-time top selling [[plug-in electric car]].<ref name="Model3TopEV" />

=== Model naming ===
During an interview recorded in 2006 Musk referred to {{nowrap|"Model 2"}} (later [[Tesla Model S]]), and to {{nowrap|"Model 3"}}.<ref name="wired-science-interview-2007" />  The Model 3 was codenamed Tesla "BlueStar" in the original business plan in 2007.<ref>{{cite tweet |title=Yes. Technically Model 3 or maybe three horizontal bars. Won't be three vertical bars.|user=elonmusk|first=Elon |last=Musk|date=August 15, 2014 |number=500378028141076483}}</ref><ref name=bbweek20070730>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2007-07-29/tesla-a-carmaker-with-silicon-valley-spark |title=Tesla: A Carmaker With Silicon Valley Spark |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |first=David |last=Welch |date=July 30, 2007 |access-date=March 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914195549/http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2007-07-29/tesla-a-carmaker-with-silicon-valley-spark |archive-date=September 14, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=LaMonica|first=Martin|title=Tesla's 'Bluestar' to be all-electric family car|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/teslas-bluestar-to-be-all-electric-family-car/|access-date=August 15, 2020|publisher=CNET|language=en|archive-date=September 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215359/https://www.cnet.com/news/teslas-bluestar-to-be-all-electric-family-car/|url-status=live}}</ref> An intended name of "{{nowrap|Model E}}" was not used owing to Ford's trademark for an electric vehicle expected to be released by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] in early 2019.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ford's all-electric 'Model E' is planned for the spring of 2019 | website=Electrek | date=August 19, 2016 | url=https://electrek.co/2016/08/19/fords-all-electric-model-e-spring-of-2019/ | access-date=September 14, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220145056/https://electrek.co/2016/08/19/fords-all-electric-model-e-spring-of-2019/ | archive-date=December 20, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Model 3'', originally stylized as "Model ☰", was announced on Musk's Twitter account on July 16, 2014.<ref>{{cite tweet|title=Confirmed: Our Gen III car, due out after Model X, will be named Model 3. |author=Tesla |user=Tesla |date=July 16, 2014 |number=489200343062814720 |access-date=July 18, 2014}}</ref> A 2015-presentation by [[JB Straubel]] used the name "{{nowrap|Model III}}".<ref name="straubel-20150830">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4D9erJtiwuU&t=7m07s|title=Tesla Reimagines the Century-old Power Grid|first=JB|last=Straubel|author-link=JB Straubel|work=Seoul Digital Forum|date=August 30, 2015|access-date=April 8, 2020|type=offset 7:07|location=Seoul|quote=Product Roadmap … 3rd Generation: Model III|via=YouTube|archive-date=February 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218160714/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4D9erJtiwuU&t=7m07s|url-status=live}}</ref>  {{As of|2016}} Musk had wanted the three models to spell ''[[Sexual intercourse|SEX]]'', but settled for "[[Leet|S3X]]".<!-- Not "S3XY" – this quote was before the Model Y --><ref>{{cite news |url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/transportation/elon-musk-wanted-to-name-his-model-3-model-e-so-teslas-brands-would-spell-sex-this-and-other-secrets-about-his-newest-car |title=Elon Musk wanted to name his Model 3 Model E so Tesla's brands would spell SEX. This and other secrets about his newest car |first=Tom |last=Randall |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |location=US |date=March 30, 2016 |access-date=April 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403041222/http://business.financialpost.com/news/transportation/elon-musk-wanted-to-name-his-model-3-model-e-so-teslas-brands-would-spell-sex-this-and-other-secrets-about-his-newest-car |archive-date=April 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In early 2017, after trademark opposition regarding [[Adidas]]'s [[three stripes]] logo,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.law360.com/ip/articles/888564/adidas-says-tesla-logo-is-too-similar-to-3-stripe-tm |title=Adidas Says Tesla Logo Is Too Similar To 3-Stripe TM |agency=[[Law360]] |location=US |publisher=Portfolio Media, Inc. |date=February 6, 2017 |access-date=February 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080719/https://www.law360.com/ip/articles/888564/adidas-says-tesla-logo-is-too-similar-to-3-stripe-tm |archive-date=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> the triplicate horizontal-bar stylization was abandoned and changed to a numeric "3".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2017/02/05/tesla-model-3-elon-musk-branding-numeric/ |title=Tesla Model 3: Elon Musk confirms the branding will be numeric – resulting in 'S3X' vehicle lineup |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |location=US |date=February 5, 2017 |access-date=February 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207131450/https://electrek.co/2017/02/05/tesla-model-3-elon-musk-branding-numeric/ |archive-date=February 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Market ===
[[File:People in line to reserve Tesla Model 3.jpg|thumb|About 125 people in line to [[pre-order]] a Model 3 in [[Walnut Creek, California]], in 2016]]

In September 2015, Tesla announced that the {{nowrap|Model 3}} would be unveiled in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bgr.com/2016/01/07/tesla-model-3-unveiling/ |title=Tesla confirms: Model 3 would be unveiled in March |first=Yoni |last=Heisler |website=BGR |date=January 7, 2016 |access-date=January 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110224421/http://bgr.com/2016/01/07/tesla-model-3-unveiling/ |archive-date=January 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2016, Musk said that the first official pictures of the car will be revealed at the end of March 2016.<ref>{{cite AV media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Off7830aMp0&t=12m26s |title=Ma vie en Tesla la rencontre avec Elon Musk |date=January 30, 2016 |access-date=April 1, 2016 |via=YouTube}}</ref> Delivery would begin in late 2017 first on the U.S.'s west coast and then move eastwards.<ref name="tm3reserve">{{cite web |title=Reserving your Model 3 |url=https://www.teslamotors.com/blog/reserving-model-3 |publisher=[[Tesla, Inc.]] |date=March 21, 2016 |access-date=March 22, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190727123721/https://www.tesla.com/blog/reserving-model-3 |archive-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref> Potential customers were first able to reserve a car at Tesla stores or online on March 31 with a refundable deposit of US$1000.<ref name="ctFaq">{{cite web |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2016/05/22/tesla-model-3-faq/ |title=Top 12 Questions On Tesla Model 3 Answered |first=Chris |last=Boylan |website=CleanTechnica |date=May 22, 2016 |access-date=January 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190143/https://cleantechnica.com/2016/05/22/tesla-model-3-faq/ |archive-date=January 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Model 3 Reservation Deposit |date=March 20, 2016 |url=https://www.teslamotors.com/support/model-3-reservation-deposit |publisher=[[Tesla Inc.]] |access-date=March 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402140129/https://www.teslamotors.com/support/model-3-reservation-deposit |archive-date=April 2, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2016, Tesla indicated that the unveiling would be on March 31, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla's Model 3 will be shown on March 31st, 'on schedule' for 2017 production |first=Chris |last=Ziegler |website=[[The Verge]] |date=February 10, 2016 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/2/10/10961864/tesla-model-3-unveiling-march-31 |access-date=May 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211091843/http://www.theverge.com/2016/2/10/10961864/tesla-model-3-unveiling-march-31 |archive-date=February 11, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Employees of Tesla<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/03/15/tesla-model-3-reservations-discount-employees/ |title=Tesla Model 3 reservations will begin early for employees, without discounts (Updated) |first=Seth |last=Weintraub |website=Electrek |date=March 15, 2016 |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204085945/https://electrek.co/2016/03/15/tesla-model-3-reservations-discount-employees/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/03/18/tesla-employees-began-ordering-their-model-3s-last-night-sight-unseen/ |title=Tesla employees began reserving their Model 3s last night, sight unseen |first=Seth |last=Weintraub |website=Electrek |date=March 18, 2016 |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204085942/https://electrek.co/2016/03/18/tesla-employees-began-ordering-their-model-3s-last-night-sight-unseen/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[SpaceX]] were given early access to Model 3 reservations,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/03/25/spacex-employees-reserve-tesla-model-3/ |title=SpaceX employees are now able to reserve the Tesla Model 3 early |first=Fred |last=Lambert |date=March 25, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204085754/https://electrek.co/2016/03/25/spacex-employees-reserve-tesla-model-3/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and about 10,000 signed up without discount,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/06/09/tesla-model-3-data-spacex-employees-reservations/ |title=Tesla Model 3: data shows that Tesla and SpaceX employees made over 10,000 reservations |first=Fred |last=Lambert |date=June 9, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=October 24, 2016 |quote=over 10,000 reservations were placed by employees |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025045628/https://electrek.co/2016/06/09/tesla-model-3-data-spacex-employees-reservations/ |archive-date=October 25, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> scheduled to receive the first batch of cars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/12/26/10-electric-cars/ |title=10 electric cars coming in the next 3 years |first=Fred |last=Lambert |date=December 26, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=December 26, 2016 |quote=Tesla will start by delivering the vehicles to employees in California (with Tesla and SpaceX it could be up to as many as 10,000 cars) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227061647/https://electrek.co/2016/12/26/10-electric-cars/ |archive-date=December 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="ctFaq" /> Current owners of Tesla vehicles got priority sales after employees but before the general public, as a reward for helping pay for the development of the Model 3.<ref name="ctFaq" /> (Employees and current owners were likely to be more tolerant of early production flaws:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1100598_tesla-reliability-take-two-are-newer-owners-less-tolerant|title=Tesla Reliability, Take Two: Are Newer Owners Less Tolerant?|website=Green Car Reports|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2020|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074812/https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1100598_tesla-reliability-take-two-are-newer-owners-less-tolerant|url-status=live}}</ref> both the Model S and the Model X had several problems at the start of their production,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.consumerreports.org/car-reliability/car-reliability-survey-2016/ |title=Consumer Reports Car Reliability Survey 2016 |magazine=[[Consumer Reports]] |date=October 24, 2016 |access-date=October 24, 2016 |quote=When a car model is brand new or "completely redesigned," that can mean new parts, new systems—and new problems. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025013526/http://www.consumerreports.org/car-reliability/car-reliability-survey-2016/ |archive-date=October 25, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="ctFaq" /> and have since improved.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/10/26/tesla-model-x-92-reduction-issue/ |title=Tesla says it reduced Model X issues by 92% amid criticism from Consumer Reports |date=October 26, 2016 |first=Jameson |last=Dow |website=Electrek |access-date=October 26, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027055814/https://electrek.co/2016/10/26/tesla-model-x-92-reduction-issue/ |archive-date=October 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On the morning of March 31, 2016, tens of thousands of people waited in lines to place the refundable deposit to reserve a Model 3 for 2017 delivery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/03/30/tesla-model-3-reservations-australia/ |title=Tesla Model 3 reservations begin with long lines in Australia [Pictures & video] |first=Fred |last=Lambert |date=March 30, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204090136/https://electrek.co/2016/03/30/tesla-model-3-reservations-australia/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://electrek.co/2016/03/31/tesla-model-3-reservations-sight-unseen/ |title=Tesla Model 3: tens of thousands reportedly reserving the $35,000 car without having seen it |website=Electrek |date=March 31, 2016 |access-date=April 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401004344/http://electrek.co/2016/03/31/tesla-model-3-reservations-sight-unseen/ |archive-date=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the Model 3 unveiling event, Tesla said that over 115,000 people had reserved the Model 3 in less than 24 hours prior;<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla's Musk: Model 3 Orders Surpassed 115,000 Within 24 Hours |first=John |last=Stoll |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=February 10, 2016 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-musk-model-3-orders-surpassed-115-000-within-24-hours-1459483890 |access-date=March 31, 2016 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401060949/http://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-musk-model-3-orders-surpassed-115-000-within-24-hours-1459483890 |archive-date=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/04/01/tesla-reservations/ |title=Tesla received 132,000 Model 3 reservations with deposits within just 24hrs – worth over $4&nbsp;billion in backlog [Updated] |first=Fred |last=Lambert |date=April 1, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204090053/https://electrek.co/2016/04/01/tesla-reservations/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> more cars than Tesla had sold by that time.<ref name="SFG02042016" /> Twenty-four hours after opening reservations, Tesla had advanced orders for over 180,000 cars.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=elonmusk |number=715934657720639488 |first=Elon |last=Musk |date=April 1, 2016 |title=Model 3 orders at 180,000 in 24 hours. Selling price w avg option mix prob $42k, so ~$7.5B in a day. Future of electric cars looking bright!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2016/04/01/200000-tesla-model-3-reservations-less-24-hours/ |title=200,000 Tesla Model 3 Reservations in Less Than 24 Hours |first=Kyle |last=Field |website=CleanTechnica |date=April 1, 2016 |access-date=February 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204170028/https://cleantechnica.com/2016/04/01/200000-tesla-model-3-reservations-less-24-hours/ |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days later, Tesla said they had 232,000 reservations.<ref name="SFG02042016">{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Tesla-Model-3-reservations-near-198-000-7223394.php| title=Tesla Model 3 reservations top 232,000| first=David R.| last=Baker| newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]| date=April 1, 2016| access-date=September 14, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905214935/http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Tesla-Model-3-reservations-near-198-000-7223394.php| archive-date=September 5, 2016| url-status=live}} ''Tesla Motors had sold 107,000 Model S cars by the end of 2015''</ref><ref name="276KModel3">{{cite news | url=http://app.ft.com/cms/s/9a163366-f9de-11e5-8e04-8600cef2ca75.html | title=Tesla Model 3 orders point to potential $11.5bn sales | first=Tim | last=Bradshaw | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | date=April 3, 2016 | access-date=April 3, 2016 | url-access=subscription | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407224542/http://app.ft.com/cms/s/9a163366-f9de-11e5-8e04-8600cef2ca75.html | archive-date=April 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> <!-- diagram -->

One week after the unveiling, Tesla said it had over 325,000 reservations, more than triple the number of [[Tesla Model S|Model S]] sedans sold by the end of 2015.<ref name="SFG02042016" /><ref name="325KModel3" /> Musk said that 5% of reservations correspond to the maximum of two vehicles allowed per customer, "suggesting low levels of speculation",<ref>{{cite tweet|user=elonmusk|number=718112326889529344 |first=Elon |last=Musk |title=Over 325k cars or ~$14B in preorders in first week. Only 5% ordered max of two, suggesting low levels of speculation. |date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> and that 93% of Model 3 reservations are from new buyers who do not currently own a Tesla.<ref name="ctFaq" /> The previous record for advance deposits on a car was the 1955 [[Citroën DS]] that had 80,000 deposits during the ten days of the [[Paris Auto Show]], while the Model 3 had 232,000 reservations in two days.<ref name="SFG02042016" />

According to Tesla's global vice-president Robin Ren, China is the second-largest market for the Model 3 after the US.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1939574/china-second-largest-market-teslas-model-3-car | title=China second-largest market for Tesla's Model 3 car | first=Phoenix | last=Kwong | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=April 28, 2016 | access-date=May 3, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501201750/http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1939574/china-second-largest-market-teslas-model-3-car | archive-date=May 1, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Tesla said the number of net reservations totaled about 373,000 {{as of|2016|05|15|lc=y|df=US}}, after about 8,000 customer cancellations and about 4,200 reservations canceled by the automaker because these appeared to be duplicates from speculators.<ref name="373K">{{cite web | url=http://insideevs.com/tesla-to-raise-2-billion-373000-people-have-reserved-a-model-3/ | title=Tesla, Musk Plan $2 Billion Stock Sale To Build Model 3, 373,000 People Reserved | first=Jay | last=Cole | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=May 18, 2016 | access-date=May 18, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519105109/http://insideevs.com/tesla-to-raise-2-billion-373000-people-have-reserved-a-model-3/ | archive-date=May 19, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Tesla to Sell $1.4 Billion in Shares for Expanded Production | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-18/tesla-to-sell-1-4-billion-in-shares-for-expanded-production | first=Dana | last=Hull | website=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=May 18, 2016 | access-date=May 18, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518222049/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-18/tesla-to-sell-1-4-billion-in-shares-for-expanded-production | archive-date=May 18, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Upon its release in July 2017, there had been over 500,000 reservations for the Model 3,<ref name="3_release_NBC">{{cite news |title=Tesla Hands Over First Model 3 Electric Cars to Early Buyers |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/tesla-hands-over-first-model-3-electric-cars-early-buyers-n787716 |date=July 29, 2017 |access-date=July 29, 2017 |via=NBC News |location=US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729044548/http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/tesla-hands-over-first-model-3-electric-cars-early-buyers-n787716 |archive-date=July 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> with Musk later clarifying there were a net of 455,000 reservations outstanding, and an average of 1,800 reservations were being added per day.<ref name="2017reservations" /><ref name="cnn_money_reservations" />

== Design ==
[[File:The Model 3 Interior.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model 3 interior]]
[[File:Tesla Model 3 Screen Dec 2020.jpg|thumb|Center-mounted {{convert|15.4|in|cm|adj=on}} [[Liquid-crystal display|LCD]] [[touchscreen]],<ref name=dash>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067728/tesla-model-3-apple-iphone-comparison|title=Tesla's Model 3 and Apple's iPhone have a few things in common|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=August 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731170204/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067728/tesla-model-3-apple-iphone-comparison|archive-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> sporting the new UI design from Tesla's December 2020 "Holiday Update"<ref>{{Cite web|last=Merano|first=Maria|date=December 25, 2020|title=Tesla rolls out 2020 Holiday Update: New Driving Visualizations, Supercharger Display Improvements and more (Release Notes)|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-holiday-update-2020-release-notes/|access-date=April 30, 2021}}</ref>]]

In 2013 design chief [[Franz von Holzhausen]] said that the Model 3 will "be an [[Audi A4]], [[BMW 3 Series]], [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class]] type of vehicle that will offer everything: range, affordability, and performance" that is targeted toward the mass market.<ref name="Franz von Holzhausen" /><ref name=automobilemag>{{cite web |title=Detroit 2013: Tesla's Family Will Grow |publisher=automobilemag.com |date=January 15, 2013 |url=http://www.automobilemag.com/news/tesla-in-detroit-our-family-will-grow-197263/ |access-date=April 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413100509/http://www.automobilemag.com/news/tesla-in-detroit-our-family-will-grow-197263/ |archive-date=April 13, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> While technology from Tesla's Model S will be used in the Model 3,<ref>{{cite web |first=Martin |last=LaMonica |title=Tesla's 'Bluestar' to be all-electric family car |publisher=CNET |date=September 24, 2008 |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10049993-54.html |access-date=November 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015184450/http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10049993-54.html |archive-date=October 15, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> it will be 20% smaller than the Model S<ref name="The Guardian">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/25/things-learned-tesla-elon-musk-electric-car |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026181527/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/25/things-learned-tesla-elon-musk-electric-car |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 26, 2013 |title=12 interesting things we learned from Tesla's Elon Musk this week |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 25, 2013 |access-date=October 26, 2013}}</ref> and have its own unique design.<ref name=ayre>{{cite web |title=Elon Musk: I Want The Model 3 To Be Different, Not Just A Smaller Model S |website=CleanTechnica |date=January 25, 2015 |url=http://cleantechnica.com/2015/01/25/elon-musk-want-model-3-different-just-smaller-model-s/ |access-date=April 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404093425/http://cleantechnica.com/2015/01/25/elon-musk-want-model-3-different-just-smaller-model-s/ |archive-date=April 4, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>

According to Tesla's CTO, [[JB Straubel]], in October 2015, most Tesla engineers were working on the 3 rather than S or X.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://chargedevs.com/newswire/tesla-shifts-focus-to-model-3-as-engineers-prepare-to-start-work-at-the-gigafactory/ |title=Tesla shifts focus to Model 3 as engineers prepare to start work at the Gigafactory |first=Charles |last=Morris |website=Charged EVs |date=October 22, 2015 |access-date=November 7, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227071335/https://chargedevs.com/newswire/tesla-shifts-focus-to-model-3-as-engineers-prepare-to-start-work-at-the-gigafactory/ |archive-date=December 27, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{youTube|k10BOn-ixEU}}</ref> Since electric cars have lower cooling needs than combustion cars, the Model 3 does not have nor need a front grille.<ref>{{cite news|date=November 17, 2015|title=Tesla veteran on electric motors vs internal-combustion engines|url=https://ecomento.com/2015/11/19/tesla-veteran-on-electric-motors-vs-internal-combustion-engines/|publisher=ecomento.com|access-date=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424071619/https://ecomento.com/2015/11/19/tesla-veteran-on-electric-motors-vs-internal-combustion-engines/|archive-date=April 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Musk intended for the final design to be released on June 30, 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teslarati.com/production-tesla-model-3-design-june-30/ |title=This Is The Tesla Model 3's Biggest Design Fail |publisher=Teslarati |location=US |date=May 6, 2016 |access-date=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509012047/http://www.teslarati.com/production-tesla-model-3-design-june-30/ |archive-date=May 9, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> but when the design was finished on July 27, it was not publicly released.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-27/elon-musk-says-it-s-pencils-down-for-tesla-s-model-3 |title=Elon Musk Says It's 'Pencils Down' for Tesla's Model 3 |first=Tom |last=Randall |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=July 27, 2016 |access-date=July 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727125410/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-27/elon-musk-says-it-s-pencils-down-for-tesla-s-model-3 |archive-date=July 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the final design of the first Model 3, any further changes would be included in future versions of the Model 3.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/6/2/11837584/tesla-model-3-design-complete-six-weeks-elon-musk |title=Tesla Model 3's design will be finished in six weeks, Elon Musk says |first=Chris |last=Ziegler |website=[[The Verge]] |location=US |date=June 2, 2016 |access-date=June 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605102158/http://www.theverge.com/2016/6/2/11837584/tesla-model-3-design-complete-six-weeks-elon-musk |archive-date=June 5, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard glass roof developed by Tesla Glass is made of the same glass used for [[Tesla Solar Roof|Tesla's roof tiles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/elon-musk-teslas-model-3-220711131.html |title=Elon Musk: Tesla is developing a special kind of glass for its Model 3 |website=Business Insider |first=Danielle |last=Muoio |date=November 1, 2016 |access-date=November 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104015438/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/elon-musk-teslas-model-3-220711131.html |archive-date=November 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Tesla Model 3 IMG 5264.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model 3 MY2021 refresh]]

In November 2020, the Model 3 was refreshed with cosmetic and internal changes, many carried over from the Model Y. The refreshed Model 3 replaced the chrome door handles, side mirror trim, window trim, and camera covers with a black finish. Double-paned front window glass, a powered trunk, new center console, and minor performance upgrades were added to all Model 3 trim levels. The car's engineering was updated to reflect Tesla's advances with the Model Y, including the introduction of a heat pump and proprietary [[octovalve]] that increases the car's heating and cooling efficiency.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Klender|first=Joey|date=November 4, 2020|title=First in-depth look at Tesla's 'refreshed' Model 3|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-refresh-first-looks-in-depth-video/|access-date=December 18, 2020|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074813/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-refresh-first-looks-in-depth-video/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Alvarez|first=Simon|date=October 9, 2020|title=Tesla Model 3 'refresh' with chrome delete, new center console spotted in factory|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-refresh-pictures/|access-date=December 18, 2020|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074815/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-refresh-pictures/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=TESMANIAN|title=Deep Looks into Tesla Model Y's Octovalve|url=https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/deep-looks-into-tesla-model-y-s-octovalve|access-date=December 18, 2020|website=TESMANIAN|language=en|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074814/https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/deep-looks-into-tesla-model-y-s-octovalve|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Production ==
{{asof|2016|12}}, Tesla planned to increase the size of the [[Tesla Factory]] in [[Fremont, California]], to accommodate Model 3 production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconvalley.com/2016/12/08/fremont-city-council-approves-major-tesla-facility-expansion-plan/ |title=Fremont: City Council approves major Tesla facility expansion plan |first=Joseph |last=Geha |website=Silicon Valley |date=December 8, 2016 |access-date=December 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209175117/http://www.siliconvalley.com/2016/12/08/fremont-city-council-approves-major-tesla-facility-expansion-plan/ |archive-date=December 9, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |title=Tesla's supply chain set for a surge |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |website=Automotive Logistics |date=July 26, 2016 |access-date=December 20, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194902/http://automotivelogistics.media/intelligence/teslas-supply-chain-set-surge |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live|quote=Getting from something like 50,000 to 500,000 units is a big, big step}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |title=Tesla warns supply chain issues could scupper its growth plans |first=Rachael |last=Hogg |website=Automotive Logistics |date=May 11, 2016 |access-date=December 20, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220195112/http://automotivelogistics.media/news/tesla-warns-supply-chain-issues-could-scupper-its-growth-plans |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live|quote= it has no experience in manufacturing vehicles at the volumes anticipated for the Model 3. [...] will need to develop "efficient, automated, low-cost manufacturing capabilities, processes and supply chains necessary to support such volumes"}}</ref>{{update after|2018|8|19|reason=What happened with the "plan" of December 2016?}}

=== Production stages ===
In a 2013 interview, [[Jerome Guillen]] discussed "BlueStar" (codename for the Model 3 project), stating that Tesla was expecting to eventually produce 400,000 cars per year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2013/08/12/tesla-la-derniere-coqueluche-de-la-silicon-valley_3460275_3234.html|title=Tesla, la dernière coqueluche de la Silicon Valley|trans-title=Tesla, the latest darling of Scilicon Valley|date=August 12, 2013|access-date=September 17, 2018|work=[[Le Monde]]|first=Sylvain|last=Cypel|language=fr|quote=Le premier, Jérôme Guillen, 41 ans, est né à [[Avignon]]. Parti de France à 20 ans, après un doctorat d'ingénierie mécanique aux Etats-Unis, un passage chez McKinsey et DaimlerBenz … Nom de code : [[Tesla BlueStar|BlueStar]]. Ce sera, promet M. Guillen, "un véhicule encore plus technologique mais moins sophistiqué. Un jour, nous aussi, ici, nous fabriquerons 400 000 voitures".|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917183206/https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2013/08/12/tesla-la-derniere-coqueluche-de-la-silicon-valley_3460275_3234.html|archive-date=September 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In May 2016 Tesla told its suppliers that it intended to double earlier-announced{{clarify|date=May 2019}} Model 3 production targets to 100,000 in 2017 and 400,000 in 2018 due to demand, which suppliers<ref name=highSupply>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-suppliers-idUSKCN0YB0CA |title=Exclusive: Suppliers question Tesla's goals for Model 3 output|date=May 20, 2016 |first1=Paul |last1=Lienert |first2=Alexandria |last2=Sage |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=May 26, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160523010434/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-suppliers-idUSKCN0YB0CA |archive-date=May 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=elc2016-05-04>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/05/04/tesla-july-1st-2017-deadline-model-3-parts-suppliers/ |title=Tesla sets July 1st 2017 as deadline for Model 3 parts with suppliers and internally |date=May 4, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=November 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106063424/https://electrek.co/2016/05/04/tesla-july-1st-2017-deadline-model-3-parts-suppliers/ |archive-date=November 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and many experts viewed as unattainable.<ref name=elc2016-11-23>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/11/23/tesla-model-3-late-adam-jonas-morgan-stanley/ |title=Tesla Model 3 will not arrive until 'very end' of 2018, says once TSLA-cheerleader Morgan Stanley's Adam Jonas |date=November 23, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=November 23, 2016 |quote=We continue to forecast a Model 3 launch at the very end of 2018 (more than 1 year later than company target) with 60k units in 2019 and 130k units in 2020. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124095107/https://electrek.co/2016/11/23/tesla-model-3-late-adam-jonas-morgan-stanley/ |archive-date=November 24, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=bower>{{cite web|url= http://insideevs.com/gm-versus-tesla-pre-production-comparison-meeting-model-3-deliveries-2017s-end/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220163040/http://insideevs.com/gm-versus-tesla-pre-production-comparison-meeting-model-3-deliveries-2017s-end/ |title=GM versus Tesla: Pre-Production Comparison for Meeting Model 3 Deliveries At 2017's End |first=George |last=Bower |date=December 20, 2016 |archive-date=December 20, 2016 | access-date=January 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the Tesla Factory, [[Electrostatic coating|paint lines]] for 500,000 automobiles commenced in 2015, and some stamping equipment for the Model 3 was operational by August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |title=Tesla Motors Model 3 Equipment 'Already Online' at Fremont Factory |first=Angela |last=Campbell |work=The Country Caller |date=August 4, 2016 |access-date=October 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013221553/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/38717-tesla-motors-inc-model-3-equipment-already-online-at-fremont-factory/ |archive-date=October 13, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Tesla bought [[Tesla Grohmann Automation|Grohmann Engineering]], experienced in automated manufacturing, in January 2017. This acquisition launched Tesla Advanced Automation Germany, which Tesla said would develop manufacturing processes to be used initially in Model 3 production.<ref name="Tesla4Q2016final" /> According to Tesla in late 2016, the company expected to invest between {{USD|2 billion}} and {{USD|2.5 billion}} in capital expenditures ahead of the start of Model 3 production.<ref name="Tesla4Q2016final" />

After the two Alpha prototypes were shown (silver and black; red was a shell) in April 2016, Tesla finished the design in late July 2016. Tesla ordered parts equivalent to 300 Beta prototypes<!-- only some, not all, to be cars --> in August 2016, preparing for development of the assembly line. As of August 2016, the company intended to make [[release candidate]]s for testing prior to actual production.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/08/01/tesla-model-3-parts-fleet-300-prototypes/ |title=Tesla Model 3: Tesla is ordering enough parts for a fleet of ~300 prototypes |date=August 1, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=November 5, 2016 |quote=it doesn't mean that the number of parts divided by the number of parts per vehicle necessarily means Tesla will build a fleet of 300 since some of the parts will be used for process validation outside of prototypes and other processes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031155822/https://electrek.co/2016/08/01/tesla-model-3-parts-fleet-300-prototypes/ |archive-date=October 31, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecountrycaller.com/49580-tesla-motors-inc-tsla-ordering-enough-model-3-parts-for-300-prototypes/ |title=Ordering Enough Model 3 Parts For 300 Prototypes |first=Angela |last=Campbell |work=The Country Caller |date=August 2, 2016 |access-date=November 5, 2016 |quote=Once the assembly line is installed following the beta prototype completion, the automaker produces several "release candidates." |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106061849/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/49580-tesla-motors-inc-tsla-ordering-enough-model-3-parts-for-300-prototypes/ |archive-date=November 6, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Tesla began building Model 3 prototypes in early February 2017 as part of the testing of the vehicle design and manufacturing processes. Tesla said in late 2016 that initial crash test results had been positive.<ref name="Tesla4Q2016final" /> Crash test results in mid-2019 were scored at 96% for protection of adults; 86% for protection of children and 74% for the way it handles "vulnerable road users" such as pedestrians. In addition, the Model 3's "safety assist" mode scored 94%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model-3-crash-europe-heatwave-climate-change/|title=Tesla Model 3 Crash Results, Europe's Record Heat, and More News From Today|last=Baker-Whitcomb|first=Alex|date=July 3, 2019|magazine=Wired|access-date=July 4, 2019|issn=1059-1028|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703232814/https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model-3-crash-europe-heatwave-climate-change/|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2016 Tesla said its production timeline was on schedule.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/10/26/tesla-model-3-progress-production-line-layout-subsystems/ |title=Tesla Model 3 progress: production line layout completed, Tesla now testing subsystems |date=October 26, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=November 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106063535/https://electrek.co/2016/10/26/tesla-model-3-progress-production-line-layout-subsystems/ |archive-date=November 6, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=2016q3confcall>{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/edited-transcript-tsla-earnings-conference-070933016.html |title=Edited Transcript of TSLA earnings conference call or presentation 26-Oct-16 9:30&nbsp;pm GMT |publisher=Yahoo |date=October 27, 2016 |access-date=December 3, 2016 |quote=Musk [39]: we're not taking any action that would cause the Model 3 timeline to be extended in any way. [41]: We're still highly confident of reaching volume production in the second half of next year. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319223453/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/edited-transcript-tsla-earnings-conference-070933016.html |archive-date=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/12/20/tesla-model-3-on-track-2017-tesla-analysts/ |title=Tesla Model 3 on track for H2 2017, Model X production 'inconsistent', says TSLA analyst after meeting with management |date=December 20, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=December 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305021939/https://electrek.co/2016/12/20/tesla-model-3-on-track-2017-tesla-analysts/ |archive-date=March 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Again in February 2017, Tesla said that vehicle development, supply chain and manufacturing are on track to support volume deliveries of the Model 3 in the second half of 2017. Limited vehicle production began in July 2017 and volume production was scheduled at that time to start by September 2017. As of February 2017, Tesla planned to [[ramp up]] production to exceed 5,000 vehicles per week in Q4 2017 and reach 10,000 vehicles per week in 2018.<ref name=Tesla4Q2016final>{{cite web |url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x929284/22C29259-6C19-41AC-9CAB-899D148F323D/TSLA_Update_Letter_2016_4Q.pdf |title=Tesla Fourth Quarter & Full Year 2016 Update |publisher=[[Tesla Inc.]] |location=Palo Alto |date=February 22, 2017 |access-date=February 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223212145/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x929284/22C29259-6C19-41AC-9CAB-899D148F323D/TSLA_Update_Letter_2016_4Q.pdf |archive-date=February 23, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Tesla missed their Q4 production target by a wide amount, as only 2,425 vehicles were produced during the entire 3-month period.<ref name="BusinessInsider2018-01-03">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.de/tesla-model-3-delivery-report-misses-fourth-quarter-2018-1?r=US&IR=T|title=Tesla misses its Model 3 deliveries by a mile|last=Ciolli|first=Joe|date=January 3, 2018|work=Business Insider|access-date=January 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104014612/http://www.businessinsider.de/tesla-model-3-delivery-report-misses-fourth-quarter-2018-1?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="qz-2018-01-03">{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/1170768/teslas-model-3-production-falls-short-as-chevy-bolt-sales-climb/|title=Tesla's Model 3 misses production targets a second time|last=Coren|first=Michael J.|date=January 3, 2018|work=Quartz|access-date=January 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104013448/https://qz.com/1170768/teslas-model-3-production-falls-short-as-chevy-bolt-sales-climb/|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Giga Nevada]] had been intended to produce battery packs for Model 3 and it was announced in January 2017 that Tesla would also manufacture drive units{{clarify|what does a "drive unit" consist of? motor? gearing? axle and wheel/brake hub?|date=October 2018}} at Giga Nevada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2016/10/15/tesla-drive-unit-production-lines-gigafactory-model-3/ |title=Tesla is building new 'drive unit production lines' at the Gigafactory, will not only manufacture battery packs |date=October 15, 2016 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |access-date=November 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911141931/http://www.thecountrycaller.com/51161-tesla-motors-inc-tsla-expects-to-spend-2-billion-on-gigafactory-construction/ |archive-date=September 11, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2017, Tesla said that installation of Model 3 manufacturing equipment was underway in the Fremont factory and at Giga Nevada, where in January, production of battery cells for energy-storage products began, which have the same form factor as the cells that will be used in Model 3.<ref name="Tesla4Q2016final" />

=== Deliveries ===
[[File:Tesla Model X and Model 3 at the unveiling event.jpg|thumb|[[Tesla Model X]] (left) and Model 3 (right) at the unveiling event on March 31, 2016]]
[[File:Tesla Model 3 dual motor - 2021-07-01.jpg|thumb|2021 updated version of Model 3]]

In February 2016 Tesla expected to repeat the delivery schedule of the S and X models: selling at first the highest-optioned cars with higher margins, to help pay for production equipment.<ref name=verge2016-02-10>{{cite web |url= https://www.theverge.com/2016/2/10/10962758/tesla-model-3-base-price-options-elon-musk |title= Don't expect the very first Tesla Model 3s to cost $35,000 |first= Chris |last= Ziegler |date= February 10, 2016 |website= [[The Verge]] |access-date= June 7, 2017 |quote= Our default plan as we've done in the past is that the initial sales are relatively highly optioned versions of the car, because we've got to pay back the investment of the tooling and everything, so it makes sense to have the higher optioned versions first. That's what we did with the S and obviously again with the X. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170801073617/https://www.theverge.com/2016/2/10/10962758/tesla-model-3-base-price-options-elon-musk |archive-date= August 1, 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> However, after the lessons learned from the complicated Model X production, Tesla changed its delivery schedule in early 2017 to produce relatively simpler cars initially, in order to reduce production risk. The first mass-produced Model 3 cars were rear-wheel drive with the long-range battery.<ref name="verge2017-03-24" /> Deliveries began in the second half of 2017 as predicted,<ref name="tm3reserve" /> but not in the numbers Tesla had hoped.<!-- not "promised" --> As industry experts had predicted, Tesla did not meet the announced delivery targets.{{clarify|date=December 2019|insufficient conjecture}}<ref name="verge2016-02-10" /><ref name=verge2017-03-24>{{cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/24/15049656/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-tweets-video |title=Elon Musk shares video of near-final Model 3, but says he won't drive one |first=Jordan |last=Golson |website=[[The Verge]] |date=March 24, 2017 |access-date=March 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325024505/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/24/15049656/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-tweets-video |archive-date=March 25, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first delivery was on July 7, 2017, to Musk himself<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2017/07/09/tesla-model-3-production-pictures/ |title=Tesla Model 3: pictures of the very first production unit at the factory |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |location=US |date=July 9, 2017 |access-date=July 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728205049/https://electrek.co/2017/07/09/tesla-model-3-production-pictures/ |archive-date=July 28, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the first 30 production units were delivered on July 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://electrek.co/2017/07/17/teslat-model-3-delivery-event-invites-owners/ |title=Tesla sends out Model 3 Delivery Event invites to select few owners |first=Fred |last=Lambert |website=Electrek |date=July 17, 2017 |access-date=July 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002551/https://electrek.co/2017/07/17/teslat-model-3-delivery-event-invites-owners/ |archive-date=July 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

