==== 2017 ====
In early July 2017 Musk forecast at least six months of serious production difficulties.<ref name="wired.com">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/story/musk-model-3-tesla-production-delays-january/|title=Tesla Delays Its Model 3 Production Goals – Again|magazine=Wired|access-date=January 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104005556/https://www.wired.com/story/musk-model-3-tesla-production-delays-january/|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla's announced goal at that time was to produce 1,500 units in the third quarter of 2017, increasing to 5,000 per week by end of December 2017,<ref name="bloomberg.com">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-02/tesla-sales-climb-as-model-3-stokes-demand-in-pricier-offerings |title=Tesla Falters With Model 3 as Initial Output Trails Forecast |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |date=October 2, 2017 |access-date=October 5, 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005033035/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-02/tesla-sales-climb-as-model-3-stokes-demand-in-pricier-offerings |archive-date=October 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> but only 260 vehicles were manufactured during the third quarter. The company blamed production bottlenecks, but said there were "no fundamental issues with the Model 3 production or supply chain" and expressed confidence about its ability to resolve the bottlenecks in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/10/02/we-understand-what-needs-to-be-fixed-tesla-says-after-bungling-model-3-production-goals/|title='We understand what needs to be fixed,' Tesla says after missing Model 3 production goals|first=Peter|last=Holley|date=October 2, 2017|access-date=October 5, 2017|work=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005002440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/10/02/we-understand-what-needs-to-be-fixed-tesla-says-after-bungling-model-3-production-goals/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-teslas-production-delays-parts-of-model-3-were-being-made-by-hand-1507321057 |title=Behind Tesla's Production Delays: Parts of Model 3 Were Being Made by Hand |first=Tim |last=Higgins |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=October 6, 2017 |access-date=October 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008002200/https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-teslas-production-delays-parts-of-model-3-were-being-made-by-hand-1507321057 |archive-date=October 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Tesla delivered just 1,542 Model 3 cars in the fourth quarter of 2017,<ref name=Tesla4Q2017final>{{cite press release |url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/4934165653x0x970775/34923C55-6853-4223-ADDA-CB3CDC1B919F/TSLA_Update_Letter_2017-4Q.pdf |title=Tesla Fourth Quarter & Full Year 2017 Update |publisher=Tesla |location=Palo Alto |date=February 7, 2017 |access-date=February 7, 2018 |quote=In Q4, we delivered 28,425 Model S and Model X vehicles and 1,542 Model 3 vehicles, totaling 29,967 deliveries. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208182745/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/4934165653x0x970775/34923C55-6853-4223-ADDA-CB3CDC1B919F/TSLA_Update_Letter_2017-4Q.pdf |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> about 2,900 less than Wall Street estimations, which were already halved previously after Tesla published the company's third quarter report.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/transportation/autos/another-missed-promise-teslas-latest-model-3-production-setback-could-mean-company-needs-more-cash|title='Another missed promise': Tesla's latest Model 3 production setback could mean company needs more cash|date=January 4, 2018|newspaper=Financial Post|access-date=January 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106002158/http://business.financialpost.com/transportation/autos/another-missed-promise-teslas-latest-model-3-production-setback-could-mean-company-needs-more-cash|archive-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=live|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> By early November 2017, Musk had postponed the target date for manufacturing 5,000 of the vehicles per week from December 2017 to March 2018.<ref name="auto">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/11/03/sleepless-nights-broken-robots-and-mounting-pressure-musk-offers-rare-glimpse-inside-teslas-production-hell/ |title=Analysis – Sleepless nights, broken robots and mounting pressure: Musk offers rare glimpse inside Tesla's 'production hell' |first=Peter |last=Holley |date=November 3, 2017 |access-date=November 5, 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105050608/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/11/03/sleepless-nights-broken-robots-and-mounting-pressure-musk-offers-rare-glimpse-inside-teslas-production-hell/ |archive-date=November 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="fortune.com" /> An analyst with Cowan and Company, an investment banking firm, said in November 2017 that "Elon Musk needs to stop over-promising and under-delivering".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-reaction/tesla-must-stop-overpromising-could-need-more-finance-analysts-idUSKBN1D21A3 |title=Tesla must stop overpromising, could need more finance: analysts |agency=Reuters |date=November 2, 2017 |access-date=November 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104234749/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-reaction/tesla-must-stop-overpromising-could-need-more-finance-analysts-idUSKBN1D21A3 |archive-date=November 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Customer deliveries totaled 1,764 units in 2017.<ref name=Tesla3Q2017final>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/5846881552x0x962149/00F6EB90-2695-44E6-8C03-7EC4E06DF840/TSLA|title=_Update_Letter_2017-3Q.pdf Tesla Third Quarter 2017 Update|publisher=Tesla|date=November 1, 2017|access-date=May 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111165022/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/5846881552x0x962149/00F6EB90-2695-44E6-8C03-7EC4E06DF840/TSLA|archive-date=January 11, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Tesla4Q2017final" />

==== 2018 ====
Prior to a planned shutdown in mid-April 2018 to further increase production, Tesla produced more than 2,000 Model 3 vehicles for three straight weeks.<ref name=Tesla1Q2018final>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x979026/44C49236-1FC2-4FD9-80B1-495ED74E4194/TSLA_Update_Letter_2018-1Q.pdf|title=Tesla First Quarter 2018 Update|publisher=Tesla|access-date=May 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527202413/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x979026/44C49236-1FC2-4FD9-80B1-495ED74E4194/TSLA_Update_Letter_2018-1Q.pdf|archive-date=May 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Global deliveries passed 100,000 units as of October 2018.<ref name=100kModel3>{{cite web |url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1119793_finalist-for-green-car-reports-best-car-to-buy-2019-tesla-model-3 |title=Finalist for Green Car Reports Best Car To Buy 2019: Tesla Model 3 |work=Green Car Reports |first=Bengt |last=Halvorson |date=November 8, 2018 |access-date=November 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110040640/https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1119793_finalist-for-green-car-reports-best-car-to-buy-2019-tesla-model-3 |archive-date=November 10, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. Model 3 sales hit 100,000 units in November 2018, reaching this milestone quicker than any previous plug-in electric model.<ref name=Model3US100K>{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-sales-november-u-s-2018/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Sales Charge Way Past Milestone Of 100,000 In U.S. |first=Eric |last=Loveday |publisher=InsideEVs.com |date=December 4, 2018 |access-date=December 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205023220/https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-sales-november-u-s-2018/ |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

During the first half of 2018, the Model 3 was the top-selling [[alternative fuel vehicle]] in California with 12,674 units, followed by the [[Toyota Prius]] conventional [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] (10,043).<ref name=AFV2Q2018CA>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Alt-Powertrain-Report-3Q-18-Release.pdf |title=California Green Vehicle Report (YTD June 2018) |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=August 2018 |access-date=October 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025071221/https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Alt-Powertrain-Report-3Q-18-Release.pdf |archive-date=October 25, 2018 |url-status=live }} ''See section: "Electric and Plug In Vehicle Segments Move Higher in 2018" – registrations through December March 2018 since 2014.''</ref>  The Model 3 was the top-selling [[plug-in electric car]] in the U.S. for 12 months in a row through December 2018, ending 2018 as the bestselling plug-in with an estimated 139,782 units delivered, the first time a plug-in car sold more than 100,000 units in one year.<ref name="US2018Tesla">{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/u-s-tesla-sales-december-2018-up/ |title=U.S. Tesla Sales in December 2018 Up By 249% |first = Mark | last = Kane |work=[[Motorsport Network#InsideEVs|InsideEVs]] |date=January 3, 2019 |access-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109111016/https://insideevs.com/u-s-tesla-sales-december-2018-up/ |archive-date=January 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="US2018sales">{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/december-2018-u-s-ev-sales-recap/ |title=December 2018 U.S. EV Sales Recap: Over 360K Secured! |first = Steven | last = Loveday |work=Inside EVs |date=January 7, 2019 |access-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109155412/https://insideevs.com/december-2018-u-s-ev-sales-recap/ |archive-date=January 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=TopUS2018>{{cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-december-2018/ | title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: December 2018 | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=January 24, 2019 | access-date=January 24, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020449/https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-december-2018/ | archive-date=January 25, 2019 | url-status=live }} ''See Graph: "Top 10 U.S. Plug-in cars (cumulative sales)" and "U.S. Plug-in Car Sales (cumulative)"''</ref> Additionally, the Model 3 ranked as the bestselling [[luxury vehicle]] in the American market in 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/niallmccarthy/2019/02/08/the-tesla-model-3-was-the-best-selling-luxury-car-in-america-last-year-infographic/ | title=The Tesla Model 3 Was The Best-Selling Luxury Car in America Last Year [Infographic] | first=Niall | last=McCarthy | work=[[Forbes]] | date=February 8, 2019 | access-date=February 23, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223184549/https://www.forbes.com/sites/niallmccarthy/2019/02/08/the-tesla-model-3-was-the-best-selling-luxury-car-in-america-last-year-infographic/#4589e2407b07 | archive-date=February 23, 2019 | url-status=live }} See infographic.</ref> The Model 3 topped plug-in electric car sales in California in 2018, with 51,293 units registered, and was the state's best selling car in the [[Near-luxury car|near luxury category]].<ref name=Cal2018>{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/california-electric-car-sales-2018/ |title=Electric Cars Outsell Hybrids in California: Tesla Model 3 Tops In Class |first=Mark |last=Kane |work=Inside EVs |date=February 21, 2019 |access-date=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222225542/https://insideevs.com/california-electric-car-sales-2018/ |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Calif4Q2018>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-18.pdf |title=New Vehicle Registrations Remained Above 2 million Units in 2018 |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=February 2019 |access-date=February 21, 2019 |volume=15 |number=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222152029/https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-18.pdf |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live }} ''See section: "Electric Vehicle Registrations Increased Sharply in 2018" – Figures for 2017 were revised.''</ref>

The Model 3 was the world's best selling plug-in electric car in 2018.<ref name=Top20Global2018>{{cite web| url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| title=Global Top 20 – December 2018| last=Jose| first=Pontes| publisher=EVSales.com| date=January 31, 2019| access-date=February 2, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013624/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| archive-date=February 1, 2019| url-status=live}} "Global sales totaled 2,018,247 plug-in passenger cars in 2018, with a BEV:PHEV ratio of 69:31, and a market share of 2.1%. The world's top selling plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2018, followed by BYD."</ref> In 2018, Elon Musk predicted that eventual global demand would likely be between 500,000 and {{nowrap|1 million}} Model 3 cars per year— ranking in between the [[BMW 3 Series]] and the [[Volkswagen Golf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LTjggW0uXBw&t=33m|first=Elon|last=Musk|author-link=Elon Musk|date=October 25, 2018|title=Tesla 2018 Q3 Earnings Call|via=YouTube|format=offset 33:00|quote=likely global demand for Model 3... it's probably on the order of anyway from 500,000 to a million cars a year, let's say, … as quick global demand for Model 3.  If you look at something like BWM 3 Series … [[BMW 3 Series]] is about half-a-million a year, globally.  And generally we find that we outcompete the BMW 3 Series quite well, so it seems logical therefore that we would have higher production …higher demand, you know;  maybe somewhere between the BMW 3 Series and the [[Volkswagen Golf]] which is about a million units a year.|access-date=October 16, 2019|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074816/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LTjggW0uXBw&t=33m|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== 2019 ====
[[File:Tesla Model 3 DCA 08 2018 0159.jpg|thumb|The Model 3 has been the world's best selling [[plug-in electric car]] for three years in a row (2018 to 2020).<ref name=Top20Global2020>{{cite web | url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2021/02/global-top-20-december-2020.html | title=Global Top 20 – December 2020 | last=Jose | first=Pontes | publisher=EVSales.com | date=February 2, 2021 | access-date=February 3, 2021 | archive-date=February 2, 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202225647/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2021/02/global-top-20-december-2020.html | url-status=live }} "Global sales totaled 3,124,793 plug-in passenger cars in 2020, with a BEV to PHEV ratio of 69:31, and a global market share of 4%. The world's top selling  plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3 with 365,240 units delivered, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2019 with 499,535 units, followed by VW with 220,220."</ref><ref name="Top20Global2018" /><ref name="Top20Global2019" />]]
[[File:Tesla Model 3 - European socket.jpg|thumb|CCS Combo 2 European socket on a Model 3]]

Retail deliveries in Europe and China began in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/more-tesla-model-3-norway/ |title=More And More Tesla Model 3 Reach Norway: Sales Imminent |last=Kane |first=Mark |work=InsideEVs |date=February 16, 2019 |access-date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216212131/https://insideevs.com/more-tesla-model-3-norway/ |archive-date=February 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-arrive-china-port-deliveries/ |title=Tesla Model 3s Arrive in Chinese Port Ready For Deliveries |work=Gasgoo News |publisher=InsideEVs |date=February 13, 2019 |access-date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217142219/https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-arrive-china-port-deliveries/ |archive-date=February 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Delivery of the first right-hand drive vehicles began in June 2019, starting with the UK<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla Model 3: first UK buyers take delivery of cars |url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/tesla-model-3-first-uk-buyers-take-delivery-cars |access-date=July 5, 2019 |work=Autocar |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705142213/https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/tesla-model-3-first-uk-buyers-take-delivery-cars |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and later in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reneweconomy.com.au/tesla-model-3-electric-vehicle-smashes-sales-records-recasts-australia-car-market-14414/|title=Tesla Model 3 electric vehicle smashes sales records, recasts Australia car market|last=Parkinson|first=Giles|date=October 2, 2019|website=RenewEconomy|language=en-AU|access-date=January 19, 2020|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074828/https://reneweconomy.com.au/tesla-model-3-electric-vehicle-smashes-sales-records-recasts-australia-car-market-14414/|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly to how the first US-made Model 3s were delivered in July 2017, the first Chinese-made Model 3 cars were delivered to employees at the end of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla delivers first China-made Model 3s to its own workers |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/30/tech/tesla-china-model-3/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=December 30, 2019 |access-date=December 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230144848/https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/30/tech/tesla-china-model-3/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2019 the Model 3 overtook the Model S as the U.S. all-time best selling all-electric car,<ref name=Top3US012019>{{cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-january-2019/ | title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: January 2019 | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=February 4, 2019 | access-date=February 6, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020207/https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-january-2019/ | archive-date=February 7, 2019 | url-status=live }} ''See Graph: "Top 10 U.S. Plug-in cars (cumulative sales)" In January 209 the Tesla Model 3 (148,046) overtook the Model S (144,767). The Chevrolet Volt (152,819) continues as the all-time best selling plug-in car in the U.S.''</ref> and, the next month, also passed the [[Chevrolet Volt]] to become the all-time top selling plug-in electric car in the U.S.<ref name="Top3US022019" />

The Tesla Model 3 ended 2019 as the world's best selling plug-in electric car for the second consecutive year, with just over 300,000 units delivered.<ref name="Top20Global2018" /><ref name=Top20Global2019>{{cite web | url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/global-top-20-december-2019.html | title=Global Top 20 – December 2019 | last=Jose | first=Pontes | publisher=EVSales.com | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074824/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/global-top-20-december-2019.html | url-status=live }} "Global sales totaled 2,209,831 plug-in passenger cars in 2019. The world's top selling  plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3 with 300,075 units delivered, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2019 with 367,820 units, followed by BYD with 229,506."</ref> The electric car also topped annual plug-in car sales in the U.S. (158,925) and California (59,514) markets for the second time in a row.<ref name="US2018Tesla" /><ref name="Cal2018" /><ref name="TopUS2019">{{cite web|last=Loveday|first=Steven|date=January 17, 2020|title=FINAL UPDATE: Quarterly Plug-In EV Sales Scorecard|url=https://insideevs.com/news/343998/monthly-plug-in-ev-sales-scorecard/|access-date=May 16, 2020|publisher=InsideEVs.com|archive-date=April 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419234131/https://insideevs.com/monthly-plug-in-sales-scorecard/|url-status=live}} ''See Chart: "2019 Monthly/Q4 Sales Chart : Annual" – The top selling models were the Tesla Model 3 with 158,925 units, the Toyota Prius Prime with 23,630, the Tesla Model X with 19,225, the Chevrolet Bolt EV with 16,418 and the Tesla Model S with 14,100 units.''</ref><ref name=CNCDA4Q2019>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-19.pdf |title=California Auto Outlook Covering Fourth Quarter 2019: State New Vehicle Market Predicted to Remain Strong in 2020 |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=February 2020 |access-date=May 16, 2020 |volume=16 |number=1 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074843/https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-19.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> And again listed as the California's best selling car in the near luxury category in 2019.<ref name="CNCDA4Q2019" />

The Model 3 also ranked as the best selling plug-in car in Europe in 2019, with over 95,000 units delivered in its first year in that market, and outselling other key premium models.<ref name=Model3TopEurope>{{cite web | url=https://www.carscoops.com/2020/02/european-car-sales-climbed-to-15-7-million-units-last-year-tesla-model-3-is-the-ev-champion/ | title=European Car Sales Climbed To 15.7 Million Units Last Year, Tesla Model 3 Is The EV Champion | first=Michael | last=Gauthier | publisher=Carscoops | date=February 19, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074845/https://www.carscoops.com/2020/02/european-car-sales-climbed-to-15-7-million-units-last-year-tesla-model-3-is-the-ev-champion/ | url-status=live }} ''Sales of the Tesla Model 3 in Europe totaled 94,495 units in 2019 (Europe 23) and topped sales in the region in the EV segment.''</ref> It also set records in Norway and the Netherlands, not only as the top selling plug-in car but also as the best selling passenger car model overall.<ref name=TopOverallSales>{{cite web | url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/01/19/tesla-model-3-1-best-selling-automobile-in-netherlands-norway-in-2019/ | title=Tesla Model 3 = #1 Best Selling Auto in Netherlands & Norway in 2019 | first=Zachary | last=Shahan | work=Clean Technica | date=January 19, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | quote=In Norway and the Netherlands, the Model 3 was the #1 best selling automobile of any kind in any class in 2019. | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074848/https://cleantechnica.com/2020/01/19/tesla-model-3-1-best-selling-automobile-in-netherlands-norway-in-2019/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="OFV2019Modell">{{cite web |url=https://ofv.no/registreringsstatistikk |title=OFV Registreringsstatistikk |language=no |trans-title=OFV Registration Statistics |author=Norwegian Road Federation (OFV) |publisher=OFV |date=January 2020 |access-date=May 10, 2020 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074850/https://ofv.no/registreringsstatistikk |url-status=live }}'' To access the sales ranking by model choose "Modell" and the tabs for "2019" and "Desember" – The Tesla Model 3 was the best selling passenger car in Norway in 2019 with 15,683 units registered.''</ref> The sales volume achieved by the Model 3 in 2019 (15,683) is the third largest in Norwegian history, exceeded only by the [[Volkswagen Beetle|Volkswagen Bobla (Beetle)]] in 1969 (16,706), and [[Volkswagen Golf]] in 2015 (16,388).<ref name=NorskModel3>{{cite web |url=https://www.dinside.no/motor/derfor-var-2019-sa-spesielt/71970723 |title=Bil-året 2019: Derfor var 2019 så spesielt |language=no |trans-title=The car of the year 2019: That's why 2019 was so special | first = Knut | last = Moberg |publisher=Dinside.no |date=December 31, 2019 |access-date=May 10, 2020 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074929/https://dinside.dagbladet.no/motor/derfor-var-2019-sa-spesielt/71970723 |url-status=live }} ''With a total of 15,473 new registered Tesla Model 3 (as of December 27, 2019), only Volkswagen has managed a higher number previously, with Bobla in 1969 (16,706 cars), and Golf in 2015 (16,388).''</ref> The Model 3 set a new record in the Netherlands for the highest registrations in one month (22,137) for any single plug-in vehicle in Europe.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/01/27/tesla-model-3-shatters-records-in-hot-european-market-ev-sales-report/ | title=Tesla Model 3 Shatters Records in Hot European Market – EV Sales Report | first=Jose | last=Pontes | work=Clean Technica | date=January 27, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074852/https://cleantechnica.com/2020/01/27/tesla-model-3-shatters-records-in-hot-european-market-ev-sales-report/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

The Model 3 also was the top selling plug-in car in Canada, Spain, Belgium, Denmark, Switzerland, Australia, New Zealand, Taiwan and Mexico.<ref name=TopModel3countries>{{cite web | url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/markets-roundup-december-2019.html | title=Markets Roundup – December 2019 | last=Jose | first=Pontes | publisher=EVSales | date=January 27, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074852/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/markets-roundup-december-2019.html | url-status=live }} ''Check for top selling plug-in car in Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Taiwan and Mexico.''</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/ | title=EV Sales 2019 | last=Jose | first=Pontes | publisher=EVSales.com | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=May 16, 2020 | archive-date=December 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074852/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2020/01/ | url-status=live }} ''Click on December sales for Spain, Belgium, Denmark, and Switzerland.''</ref>

==== 2020 ====
Until 2019, the [[Nissan Leaf]] was the world's best selling [[plug-in electric car]], with global sales of 450,000 units by December 2019.<ref name=Leaf450K>{{cite press release |title=The "E" side of EV: Nissan brings excitement from the road to the track with LEAF Nismo RC unleashed for the first time in Europe |url=https://europe.nissannews.com/en-GB/releases/release-a9f393adfcdb4c875b17ca02b001a9dc-nissan-brings-excitement-from-the-road-to-the-track-with-leaf-nismo-rc-unleashed-for-the-first-time-in-europe |publisher=Nissan Europe |location=Valencia, Spain |date=January 20, 2020 |access-date=May 3, 2020 |archive-date=May 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200505080000/https://europe.nissannews.com/en-GB/releases/release-a9f393adfcdb4c875b17ca02b001a9dc-nissan-brings-excitement-from-the-road-to-the-track-with-leaf-nismo-rc-unleashed-for-the-first-time-in-europe |url-status=live }}</ref> The Tesla Model 3 surpassed Leaf sales in early 2020 to become the world's best selling plug-in electric car ever.<ref name="Model3TopEV" /> Global sales totaled about 814,000 units overall up to December 2020.<ref name="Top20Global2020" /><ref name="Tesla3Q2017final" /><ref name="Tesla4Q2017final" /><ref name="Tesla4Q2018final" /><ref name="tesla-2020q1" /> The Model 3, with 365,240 global deliveries, was the world's best selling plug-in passenger car in 2020 for the third consecutive year.<ref name="Top20Global2018" /><ref name="Top20Global2019" /><ref name="Top20Global2020" />

In 2020, the Model 3 was the bestselling plug-in car in China (137,459) and the U.S. (95,135).<ref name=TopEVs2020US>{{cite news|url=https://www.autonews.com/mobility-report/teslas-commanding-lead-us-evs-illustrated-registration-report |title=Tesla's commanding lead in U.S. EVs illustrated by registration report | first = C.J. | last = Moore |work=[[Automotive News]] | date=February 14, 2021 |access-date=February 14, 2021 }} ''According to [[Experian]], in 2020 the top U.S. EVs by registrations were the Tesla Model 3 (95,135), Tesla Model Y (71,344), Chevrolet Bolt EV (19,664), the Tesla Model X (19,652), Tesla Model S (14,430) and the Nissan Leaf (8,972). All four Tesla models accounted for 200,561 registrations, up 16% from 2019.''</ref><ref name="TopNEVsChina2020">{{cite news|url=http://english.sdchina.com/show/4593846.html |title=Domestic EV makers rival Tesla in China, can they win? |work=SDchina.com |date=February 5, 2021 |access-date=February 19, 2021}} ''See table: Top 10 NEV sold in China in 2020.''</ref> The Model 3 also was the most popular plug-in electric car in California in 2020 (38,580), as well as the state's best selling car in the near luxury category.<ref name=CNCDA4Q2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-20.pdf |title=California Auto Outlook Covering Fourth Quarter 2020: State New Light Vehicle Registrations Predicted to Approach 1.8 Million Units in 2021 |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=February 2021 |access-date=February 8, 2021 |volume = 17| number=1}} ''A total of 132,742 plug-in electric passenger cars (101,628 BEVs and 31,114 PHEVs) and were registered in 2020. Registration figures between 2016 and 2019 were revised, resulting in significantly higher estimates than previously reported through 2019.''</ref> The Model 3 has topped both California's and the U.S. national plug-in car sales for three years in-a-row, from 2018 to 2020.<ref name="TopEVs2020US" /><ref name="US2018sales" /><ref name="TopUS2019" /><ref name="CNCDA4Q2020" />

==== 2021 ====
In 2021, the Model 3 became the all-time bestselling electric vehicle in the Netherlands with over 78,996 cars registered at the end of June 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nederlandelektrisch.nl/actueel/verkoopcijfers|title = Nederland Elektrisch – Cijfers en statistieken EV's in Nederland}}</ref> The Model 3 became the first electric car to sell over 1&nbsp;million units globally in June 2021.<ref name="1miModel3" />

It was also the bestselling electric vehicle of 2021 in the UK, with 34,783 registered, beating the second most popular electric car, the [[Kia e-Niro]], by over 22,500 registrations. These figures also made the Model 3 the second bestseller in the UK new car market in 2021, only beaten by the [[Opel Corsa|Vauxhall Corsa]], a cheaper [[B-segment]] vehicle. The 9,612 Model 3s sold in December were more than double the sales of any other car in that month.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Car Registrations: December 2021 and Year-To-Date|url=https://www.smmt.co.uk/vehicle-data/car-registrations/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119033830/https://www.smmt.co.uk/vehicle-data/car-registrations/|archive-date=January 19, 2022|website=[[SMMT]]|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

In October 2021, [[The Hertz Corporation|Hertz car rental]] ordered 100,000 full-price {{nowrap|Model 3}} cars for its rental fleet.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jolly|first=Jasper|date=October 25, 2021|title=Tesla breaks $1tn valuation barrier after Hertz orders 100,000 vehicles|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2021/oct/25/tesla-model-3-is-first-battery-electric-car-to-top-europe-monthly-sales-chart|access-date=October 26, 2021|quote=the US electric car pioneer received an order for 100,000 of its vehicles from the rental company Hertz.}}</ref><ref name="musk-20211026">{{cite tweet|number=1452794619410927625|user=elonmusk|title=To be clear, cars sold to Hertz have no discount. Same price as to consumers.|first=Elon |last=Musk|date=October 26, 2021|access-date=October 26, 2021}}</ref>

=== Concerns ===
In May 2018 [[Consumer Reports]] found "big flaws, such as long stopping distances in our emergency braking test and difficult-to-use controls", finding the braking distance was worse than a Ford F-150 full-size truck, and branding the Model 3 "not recommended".  Tesla responded to the claims with concern and, over the next weekend, released an [[Over-the-air programming|OTA update]] for the anti-lock braking algorithm.  Consumer Reports, impressed with the prompt OTA update, verified the improved braking performance and changed their rating to a recommended model.<ref name="Consumer Reports May 30, 2018 braking update">{{cite web |title=Tesla Model 3 Gets CR Recommendation After Braking Update |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/car-safety/tesla-model-3-gets-cr-recommendation-after-braking-update/ |first=Patrick |last=Olsen |work=Consumer Reports |location=US |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=June 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531211817/https://www.consumerreports.org/car-safety/tesla-model-3-gets-cr-recommendation-after-braking-update/ |archive-date=May 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Wired May 30, 2018 brake fix OTA">{{cite magazine |last1=Marshall |first1=Aarian |title=Tesla's Quick Fix for Its Braking System Came From the Ether |url=https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model3-braking-software-update-consumer-reports/ |magazine=Wired |location=US |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=June 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019115808/https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model3-braking-software-update-consumer-reports/ |archive-date=October 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2019 Consumer Reports revoked the Model 3 recommendation because "many customers have reported problems with the [car], including loose body trim and glass defects."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/21/tech/consumer-reports-tesla-model-3/index.html|title=Consumer Reports no longer recommends the Tesla Model 3|work=[[CNN Business]]|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=February 21, 2019|access-date=February 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221194657/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/21/tech/consumer-reports-tesla-model-3/index.html|archive-date=February 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As with Model S and Model X, Model 3 production flaws were reduced over time.<ref name=bloombergSurvey>{{cite web |first1 = Tom | last1 = Randall | first2 = Dean | last2 = Halford | first3 = Cedric | last3 = Sam |title=The Tesla Model 3 Survey 5,000 Tesla Owners Told Us What Elon Musk Got Right and Wrong |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2019-tesla-model-3-survey/ |website=bloomberg.com |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=October 29, 2019 |access-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029164702/https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2019-tesla-model-3-survey/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  In November 2019 Consumer Reports reinstated the Model 3 recommendation, claiming it was the fifth-most reliable of twelve compact luxury cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/15/tesla-model-3-s-consumer-reports-recommended-list/|title=Tesla's Model 3 and S are (once again) recommended by 'Consumer Reports'|work=[[Engadget]]|last=Moon|first=Mariella|date=November 15, 2019|access-date=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117060147/https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/15/tesla-model-3-s-consumer-reports-recommended-list/|archive-date=November 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

During long-term testing of a Model 3 in December 2019, ''Car and Driver'' experienced a rear [[inverter]] [[short circuit|short]] after {{convert|5286|mi}} and 3 months of ownership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30383959/tesla-model-3-repaired-after-breakdown/|title=Our Tesla Model 3 Is Up and Running Again after Getting a New Rear-Motor Assembly|date=January 2, 2020|website=Car and Driver|access-date=January 12, 2020|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074859/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30383959/tesla-model-3-repaired-after-breakdown/|url-status=live}}</ref>  It was their first long-term vehicle to suffer such a major failure while parked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30361800/tesla-model-3-long-term-failure-stranded-while-parked/|title=Our Tesla Model 3 Suffered a Catastrophic Failure While Parked|date=December 31, 2019|website=Car and Driver|access-date=January 12, 2020|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074859/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30361800/tesla-model-3-long-term-failure-stranded-while-parked/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2020, due to the Covid-19 outbreak, closure of the Shanghai factory at the end of January, and supply chain issues, Tesla used the 2.5 version processor instead of the 3.0 processor that Chinese users expected to find in their vehicles. This led to mass complaints. Tesla promised to upgrade the hardware free of charge once the supply chain is restored.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51736405|title=Tesla downgraded Chinese car tech because of virus|date=March 4, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=March 5, 2020|language=en-GB|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074859/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51736405|url-status=live}}</ref>

The 2021 Tesla Model 3 vehicles built on or after April 27, 2021, had modified Forward Collison Warning (FCW) and Automatic Emergency Braking (AEB) safety features, resulting in lower Consumer Reports and Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) scores. The change was from using Radar to Camera technology called Tesla Vision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nhtsa.gov/vehicle/2021/TESLA/MODEL%2525203/4%252520DR/AWD|title=Recommended Safety Technologies|date=May 28, 2021|work=NHTSA|access-date=May 28, 2021|language=en-GB|archive-date=May 31, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210531154920/https://www.nhtsa.gov/vehicle/2021/TESLA/MODEL%25203/4%2520DR/AWD|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] has open an investigation over phantom braking in these new vehicles.<ref>[https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a39250157/tesla-no-radar-sensor-model-s-model-x/ Tesla Stops Putting Radar Sensors in New Model S and Model X EVs]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-60432351 Tesla investigated over 'phantom braking' problem]</ref>

In May 2022, a [[relay attack]] was discovered where an attacker could gain remote control of a Model 3 (or a Model Y) if they could get within range of a [[Bluetooth]] key of the owner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Page |first1=Carly |title=New Bluetooth attack can remotely unlock Tesla vehicles and smart locks |url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/05/18/bluetooth-attack-unlock-tesla/ |website=TechCrunch |date=May 18, 2022 |access-date=May 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2022/05/new-bluetooth-hack-can-unlock-your-tesla-and-all-kinds-of-other-devices/2/ |title= New Bluetooth hack can unlock your Tesla—and all kinds of other devices |website= arstechnica.com |first= Dan |last= Goodin |date= May 18, 2022 |access-date= May 18, 2022}}</ref>

== Specifications ==
[[File:First Model 3 production cars ready for delivery.jpg|thumb|First production Tesla Model 3 cars ready for the delivery event on July 28, 2017]]

=== Engineering and changes ===
When production began in 2017, the base Model 3 was announced to have a 50-kWh battery with a range of about {{convert|220|miles|abbr=out}} while the optional 75-kWh battery would have a range of about {{convert|310|miles|abbr=out}}.<ref name="Battery" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://futurism.com/take-an-in-depth-look-at-the-tesla-model-3s-new-battery-pack-architecture/ |title=Take an In-Depth Look at the Tesla Model 3's New Battery Pack Architecture|date=August 25, 2017|access-date=November 6, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015125/https://futurism.com/take-an-in-depth-look-at-the-tesla-model-3s-new-battery-pack-architecture/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla did not produce base Model 3s in 2017 or 2018. The battery uses 2170-size lithium-ion cells.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |title=Tesla Model 3: Exclusive first look at Tesla's new battery pack architecture|date=August 24, 2017|access-date=November 6, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003616/https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Tesla Model 3 battery options">{{cite news |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-partner-panasonic-20-30-percent-energy-density-increase// |title=Tesla partner Panasonic says 30% energy density increase in lithium-ion batteries possible |first=Carolyn |last=F |website=Teslarati |date=April 10, 2017 |access-date=November 6, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022854/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-partner-panasonic-20-30-percent-energy-density-increase// |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The 350-volt (nominal, 400v max) Model 3 battery packs are made of four longitudinal modules each containing the groups (bricks). The Standard Range version carries 2,976 cells arranged in 96 groups of 31. The Long Range version carries 4,416 cells arranged in 96 groups of 46, and weighs<ref name=epa2017>{{cite web |last1=Govindasamy |first1=Kannan |title=RequestforissuanceofanewcertificateofConformity– Initial application for MY2017 Model 3 ‐ Touring |url=https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp?docid=40001&flag=1 |publisher=Environmental Protection Agency |date=June 21, 2017 |access-date=May 25, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190525092128/https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp%3Fdocid%3D40001%26flag%3D1 |archive-date=May 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{Convert|480|kg|lbs|order=flip|abbr=}} in a 0.40 m³ volume; a density of 150 Wh/kg.<ref name=tm3conf2019>{{cite web |title=Request for issuance of a new certificate of Conformity |url=https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp?docid=46584&flag=1 |page=36 |date=January 28, 2019 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074858/https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp?docid=46584&flag=1 |url-status=live }}<!-- includes [[Monroney sticker]]s to upload, like https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Electric_99mpge_500px.jpg --></ref><ref name=cleantechnica2018-07-09>{{cite web |last1=Arcus |first1=Christopher |title=Tesla Model 3 & Chevy Bolt Battery Packs Examined |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2018/07/08/tesla-model-3-chevy-bolt-battery-packs-examined/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=July 9, 2018 |access-date=December 1, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191210192933/https://cleantechnica.com/2018/07/08/tesla-model-3-chevy-bolt-battery-packs-examined/ |archive-date=December 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The car's onboard [[rectifier|AC/DC converter]] is 11&nbsp;kW.<ref name="Tesla Model 3 specs" /> In Europe this requires [[Three-phase electric power]], otherwise single-phase power is 7.4&nbsp;kW.<ref name=evdbTM>{{cite web |title=Tesla Model 3 |url=https://ev-database.org/car/1555/Tesla-Model-3#charge-table |website=EV Database |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20211122203213/https://ev-database.org/car/1555/Tesla-Model-3 |archive-date=November 22, 2021 |language=en |url-status=live}}</ref>

Tesla continues to improve the design of the 2170 battery cell and introduces incremental improvements into the manufacturing line periodically.<ref name=cleantechnica20190105>{{cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/01/05/tesla-gigafactory-tour-shows-why-teslas-batteries-constantly-improving/ |title=Tesla Gigafactory Tour Shows Where Tesla Continuously Drives Down Battery Costs|date=January 6, 2019|website=CleanTechnica |access-date=January 25, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190126000724/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/01/05/tesla-gigafactory-tour-shows-why-teslas-batteries-constantly-improving/ |archive-date=January 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla began manufacture of the "lighter, better, cheaper"<ref name="electrek20181113" /> 2170 cell during 2018, with a company goal of reducing the [[cost]] of assembled battery packs to {{USD|100 per kilowatt-hour (kWh)}} by December 2018, and moving the new cell into volume production at Giga Nevada during the first quarter of 2019. [[Electrek]] reported in late 2018 that the improved battery cell design was needed to further reduce battery costs as Tesla was planning to begin to deliver the Model 3 Standard Range for the promised base price of {{USD|35,000}} the following year.<ref name=electrek20181113>[https://electrek.co/2018/11/13/tesla-battery-cells-improved/ Tesla is working on new and improved battery cells] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190126164251/https://electrek.co/2018/11/13/tesla-battery-cells-improved/ |date=January 26, 2019 }}, Electrek, November 13, 2018. Retrieved January 26, 2019.</ref>{{update after|2019|10|1|}}<!-- did they achieve this goal of 100 per kilowatt-hour by the date they intended? -->

The [[power inverter|inverter]] for the Model 3 drive unit uses 24 pairs of [[silicon carbide#Power electronic devices|silicon carbide]] (SiC) [[MOSFET]] chips rated for 650 volts{{clarify|is it known what the model is? can we ascertain what the current specification is? so as to improve the encyclopedic description here.|date=January 2020}} each.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.systemplus.fr/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/SP18413-STM_SiC_Module_Tesla_Model_3_Inverter_sample-3.pdf |title=STMicroelectronics SiC Module in Tesla Model3 Inverter|publisher=SystemPlus Consulting|date=June 25, 2018|first=Elena|last=Barbarini |quote=full SiC power module, in its Model 3. … STMicroelectronics … Tesla inverter … 24 1-in-1 power modules … module contains two [[Silicon Carbide|SiC]] MOSFETs|access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-date=December 27, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074859/https://www.systemplus.fr/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/SP18413-STM_SiC_Module_Tesla_Model_3_Inverter_sample-3.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2018 media reported that a Model 3 prototype was seen in California and Nevada while towing a trailer in an apparent evaluation of a [[tow bar]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://electrek.co/2018/07/31/tesla-model-3-towing-capacity/ |title= Tesla Model 3 spotted testing towing capacity |work= Electrek |first= Fred |last= Lambert |date= July 31, 2018 |access-date= April 13, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190530225729/https://electrek.co/2018/07/31/tesla-model-3-towing-capacity/ |archive-date= May 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> In May 2019 Tesla started offering an optional tow bar rated for {{convert|2000|lb|kg}} available with Standard Range Plus and Long Range for the European Model 3.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/model3/design?redirect=no#paint |title= Design your Model 3 |website= tesla.com |access-date= May 8, 2019 |archive-date= December 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074958/https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/model3/design?redirect=no#paint |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://electrek.co/2019/05/08/tesla-model-3-tow-hitch/ |title= Tesla launches tow hitch for Model 3 |work= Electrek |first= Fred |last= Lambert |date= May 8, 2019 |access-date= June 28, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190605191349/https://electrek.co/2019/05/08/tesla-model-3-tow-hitch/ |archive-date= June 5, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/videos/model-3-tow-hitch |title= Model 3 Tow Hitch|website= tesla.com|date= May 14, 2019|access-date= May 14, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190519194744/https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/videos/model-3-tow-hitch |archive-date= May 19, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> Towing a trailer may increase consumption by 40%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klender |first1=Joey |title=Tesla Model 3 takes on World War II-era trailer in range efficiency towing test |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-towing-range-impact/ |website=TESLARATI |date=March 13, 2020 |quote=448 Watt-hours per mile (Wh/mile) .. with trailer. 320 Wh/mi .. without a trailer. |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074901/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-towing-range-impact/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Towing capacity {{cvt|1000|kg}}. Towing is not available for the Performance model.

The Model 3 uses regenerative braking, which was tweaked and improved in October 2018 via a software update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2018/10/25/tesla-model-3-regenerative-braking-software-update/ |title=Tesla improves regenerative braking on Model 3 through over-the-air software update|first=Fred|last=Lambert |date=October 25, 2018|access-date=October 25, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181026064538/https://electrek.co/2018/10/25/tesla-model-3-regenerative-braking-software-update/ |archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2019 Tesla released a software update including a 5% power upgrade and peak power optimization to owners of the Model 3, via software version 2019.36.2.1, which showed noticeable improvements in acceleration and overall speed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-acceleration-boost-upgrade-2k/ |title=Tesla is hinting at a paid 'Acceleration Boost' upgrade for the Model 3 |website=teslarati.com |date=December 18, 2019 |access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191222011924/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-acceleration-boost-upgrade-2k/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2019, Tesla offered Long Range dual-motor Model 3 owners who had software version 2019.40.2 the option to purchase a US$2000 "Acceleration Boost" software upgrade enabling a Sport driving mode,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autoblog.com/2019/12/19/tesla-model-3-speed-boost/ |title=Tesla Model 3 owners can go quicker with a click |website=autoblog.com |access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-date=December 27, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201227074901/https://www.autoblog.com/2019/12/19/tesla-model-3-speed-boost/ |url-status=live }}</ref> advertised to reduce 0-{{convert|60|mph|0|abbr=on}} time from 4.4s to 3.9s.  Road testing confirmed better-than-expected acceleration with drivers in Sport mode reaching 0-{{convert|60|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 3.67s from standstill and 3.47s with a 1-foot rollout.<ref name="teslamotorsclub.com Dragy 0-60mph Results">{{cite web |url=https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/attachments/3-67zeroto60-png.489974/ |title=teslamotorsclub.com Dragy 0-60mph Results |website=teslamotorsclub.com |access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191222004547/https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/attachments/3-67zeroto60-png.489974/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Structurally, the Model 3 is mostly steel, and most body panels are aluminum.<ref name=nikkei2016-09-12>{{cite news |url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Tech-Science/Tech/The-company-that-helps-Tesla-make-aluminum-look-sexy?page=2 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160913201501/http://asia.nikkei.com/Tech-Science/Tech/The-company-that-helps-Tesla-make-aluminum-look-sexy?page=2 |title=The company that helps Tesla make aluminum look sexy |first=Yoshifumi |last=Uesaka |date=September 12, 2016 |archive-date=September 13, 2016 |url-status=live |newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|access-date=September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/news/334582/tesla-model-3-aluminum-steel-high-strength-steel-mix-revealed/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Aluminum, Steel, High-Strength Steel Mix Revealed}}</ref>

The {{cvt|185|cm|ft}} width was chosen to fit with [[automated parking system]]s in Japan.{{Citation needed|date=July 2020}} Due to its smaller size, the Model 3 is expected to consume less energy than the Model Y, and thus have longer range.<ref name="ct2019-06-08">{{cite web |last1=Field |first1=Kyle |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190821223314/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |archive-date=August 21, 2019 |url-status=live |title=Streamlining Manufacturing of the Tesla Model 3 For The Model Y |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=June 8, 2019 |quote=the Model Y is notably larger than the Model 3 and has a larger frontal surface area as a result. Combined with its 8–10% heavier build, that will result in a lower efficiency than the 3}}</ref>

Traditional [[Electronic stability control|stability control]] is not made for dual-motor control or the faster response time in electric motors, and Tesla modified the control unit.<ref name=tu2019-05-24>{{cite web |last1=Valle |first1=Marius |title=How Tesla engineers work with Model 3 |url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=no&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tu.no%2Fartikler%2Fslik-jobber-teslas-ingeniorer-med-model-3%2F465394 |publisher=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]] |date=May 24, 2019 |quote=https://www.tu.no/artikler/slik-jobber-teslas-ingeniorer-med-model-3/465394 }}</ref> The motors have magnets arranged in a [[Halbach array]].<ref name="ct2019-04-29">{{cite web |title=Industry Expert On Tesla's Motors: "They've Got Magic!" |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/28/industry-expert-on-teslas-motors-theyve-got-magic/ |website=CleanTechnica |date= April 29, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190921053750/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/28/industry-expert-on-teslas-motors-theyve-got-magic/ |archive-date=September 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Battery management system#Thermal management|cooling system]] is integrated to reduce size and cost.<ref name=jalop2018-12-12>{{cite web |title=The Tesla Model 3 'Superbottle' Easter Egg Is a Fascinating Packaging Solution |url=https://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-3s-superbottle-easter-egg-is-a-fascin-1830992728 |website=Jalopnik |date= December 12, 2018|language=en-us |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191219054117/https://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-3s-superbottle-easter-egg-is-a-fascin-1830992728 |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>
